  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "The evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation has been significant:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal activity\n- Limited scope and enforcement mechanisms\n\n2. 1980s Developments\n- Increased awareness of money laundering through drug trafficking\n- Introduction of mandatory reporting requirements\n- Enhanced financial transaction monitoring\n\n3. International Cooperation\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Global standards for combating money laundering\n- Recommendations for national legal frameworks\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded AML regulations\n- Stronger focus on terrorist financing\n- Increased information sharing between agencies\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Broader definition of financial crimes\n\n6. Technological Adaptation\n- AI and machine learning in detecting suspicious activities\n- Real-time transaction monitoring\n- Advanced risk assessment techniques\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, becoming more sophisticated and comprehensive.",
